\chapter{The end}

Congratulations! You've read as much as I've written so far. (The length is
pitiful, I know, I'm working on that\dots). Anyway, the book is obviously not
finished, so what should you do in the meantime?

Well, read more math of course!

Here are my recommendations, in no particular order:

\begin{itemize}
  \item \xtb{\fullcite{expeditions}}

    This book is an excellent overview of the history of mathematics. It also
    lightly touches upon the mathematics itself. It's a good book to get
    yourself interested in mathematics, without actually getting too deep into
    the math.

  \item \xtb{\fullcite{savin-number-theory}}

    This is a collection of lecture notes about number theory from a professor
    at my university. Number theory is a good way to familiarize yourself with
    the guts of mathematics without tackling the super tricky problems. Number
    theory is also the basis for most modern cryptography. Thus, number theory
    is a good thing to learn if you are interested in cryptography.

    This ``book'' is reasonably readable. However, because it is a series of
    lecture notes, it is assumed that a knowledgeable person is explaining
    things to you if you don't understand them. If you're willing to spend hours
    combing through lecture notes to learn something, I recommend this book.

  \item \xtb{\fullcite{hungerford}}

    This is an incredibly dense book, not suitable for the average
    person. Nonetheless, is covers a lot of what I want to cover in this book,
    and does so in a reasonably rigorous manner.

  \item \xtb{\fullcite{taylor-analysis}}

    This is also a very dense book not suitable for the layman. However, it's a
    good introduction to rigorous mathematics.

    This was originally a series of lecture notes also by a professor at my
    university, much like \cite{savin-number-theory}. It is, however, somewhat
    more evolved, and can be considered a full textbook.

  \item \xtb{\fullcite{lyah}}

    This is the namesake and inspiration for this book. It's not entirely
    relevant, but I have to mention it.

  \item \xtb{\fullcite{hhg}}

    Completely unrelated to the contents of this book. Nonetheless, it's a very
    good book, and you should read it if you haven't already.

  \item \xtb{\fullcite{princeton}}

    This book is over 1000 pages long, in 8 point font. Every mathematician has
    this book on his shelf to make themselves look smart, but nobody has ever
    actually read it. Nonetheless, if you want your friends to take you
    seriously, you have to own a copy of this book, and pretend like you have
    tried to read it.
\end{itemize}

Okay, I now have a pile of books on my desk so I can write down their
information. The pile just collapsed and terrified my cat, so I think that's
enough books for now.

